{"parse":{"title":"Baren (printing tool)","pageid":3127594,"revid":832286565,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><div role=\"note\" class=\"hatnote navigation-not-searchable\">For the French commune, see <a href=\"/wiki/Baren,_Haute-Garonne\" title=\"Baren, Haute-Garonne\">Baren, Haute-Garonne</a>.</div>\n<p><b>Baren</b> (\u99ac\u9023\u3001\u99ac\u695d) <i><span class=\"unicode haudio\"><span class=\"fn\"><span style=\"white-space:nowrap\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Baren.ogg\" title=\"About this sound\"><img alt=\"About this sound\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8a/Loudspeaker.svg/11px-Loudspeaker.svg.png\" width=\"11\" height=\"11\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8a/Loudspeaker.svg/17px-Loudspeaker.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8a/Loudspeaker.svg/22px-Loudspeaker.svg.png 2x\" data-file-width=\"20\" data-file-height=\"20\" /></a>&#160;</span><a href=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/7/79/Baren.ogg\" class=\"internal\" title=\"Baren.ogg\">listen</a></span>&#160;<small class=\"metadata audiolinkinfo\" style=\"cursor:help;\">(<a href=\"/wiki/Wikipedia:Media_help\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Wikipedia:Media help\"><span style=\"cursor:help;\">help</span></a>\u00b7<a href=\"/wiki/File:Baren.ogg\" title=\"File:Baren.ogg\"><span style=\"cursor:help;\">info</span></a>)</small></span></i> is a disk-like hand tool with a flat bottom and a knotted handle used in <a href=\"/wiki/Japanese_woodblock_printing\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Japanese woodblock printing\">Japanese woodblock printing</a>. It is used to burnish (firmly rub) the back of a sheet of paper, lifting ink from the block.\n</p>\n<div id=\"toc\" class=\"toc\"><input type=\"checkbox\" role=\"button\" id=\"toctogglecheckbox\" class=\"toctogglecheckbox\" style=\"display:none\" /><div class=\"toctitle\" lang=\"en\" dir=\"ltr\"><h2>Contents</h2><span class=\"toctogglespan\"><label class=\"toctogglelabel\" for=\"toctogglecheckbox\"></label></span></div>\n<ul>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-1\"><a href=\"#Construction\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">1</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Construction</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-2\"><a href=\"#Alternatives\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">2</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Alternatives</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-3\"><a href=\"#References\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">3</span> <span class=\"toctext\">References</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-4\"><a href=\"#External_links\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">4</span> <span class=\"toctext\">External links</span></a></li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Construction\">Construction</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Baren_(printing_tool)&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: Construction\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"thumb tright\"><div class=\"thumbinner\" style=\"width:182px;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Coiled_cord_for_a_baren.gif\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/b/be/Coiled_cord_for_a_baren.gif/180px-Coiled_cord_for_a_baren.gif\" width=\"180\" height=\"186\" class=\"thumbimage\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/b/be/Coiled_cord_for_a_baren.gif/270px-Coiled_cord_for_a_baren.gif 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/b/be/Coiled_cord_for_a_baren.gif 2x\" data-file-width=\"327\" data-file-height=\"337\" /></a>  <div class=\"thumbcaption\"><div class=\"magnify\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Coiled_cord_for_a_baren.gif\" class=\"internal\" title=\"Enlarge\"></a></div>A coiled braided cord forms the core of the baren</div></div></div>\n<div class=\"thumb tright\"><div class=\"thumbinner\" style=\"width:182px;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Baren2.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/a/a9/Baren2.jpg/180px-Baren2.jpg\" width=\"180\" height=\"236\" class=\"thumbimage\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/a/a9/Baren2.jpg/270px-Baren2.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/a/a9/Baren2.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"320\" data-file-height=\"420\" /></a>  <div class=\"thumbcaption\"><div class=\"magnify\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Baren2.jpg\" class=\"internal\" title=\"Enlarge\"></a></div>Finishing the wrapping by pressing the baren down firmly with the left hand to tighten the wrapping and twisting the sheath with the right hand to form a handle.</div></div></div>\n<p>The baren is made of layers.  A flat coil of <a href=\"/wiki/Braid\" title=\"Braid\">braided</a> cord forms the core. This is placed on a disk (<i>ategawa</i>) consisting of 30\u201340 sheets of high-grade long-fibred hosokawa paper, wrapped in tissue and black <a href=\"/wiki/Lacquer\" title=\"Lacquer\">lacquer</a>. This is covered by a thin bamboo sheath (<i>takenokawa</i>) twisted in such a manner as to form the handle on the top.<sup id=\"cite_ref-McGregorIshida2016_1-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-McGregorIshida2016-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> According to <a href=\"/wiki/Hiroshi_Yoshida\" title=\"Hiroshi Yoshida\">Hiroshi Yoshida</a>'s manual <i>Japanese Woodblock Printing</i> (1939) the <i><a href=\"/wiki/Phyllostachys_bambusoides\" title=\"Phyllostachys bambusoides\">madake</a></i> species of bamboo, grown in Kyushu, southwest Japan, is considered the best one to use.<sup id=\"cite_ref-hiroshi_2-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-hiroshi-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>The bamboo-sheath covering the baren may need to be renewed after a day's printing.  Rewrapping requires great skill; a printer's ability is sometimes judged by their competence carrying out this work.<sup id=\"cite_ref-hiroshi_2-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-hiroshi-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>The disk inside the baren takes 40\u201350 days to create, as the craftsman glues one sheet of paper on the disk each day.  The disk must then dry for a year before the baren is assembled.  The coil and covering of the baren are woven and formed from parts of the bamboo plant, requiring the skill of a true master. Only one known person in Japan is still making traditional (<i>hon</i>) baren for a living \u2014 Hidehiko Goto of the Kikuhide workshop.\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Alternatives\">Alternatives</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Baren_(printing_tool)&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: Alternatives\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>Large wooden spoons are also used as burnishing tools in printmaking, glass jars with a smooth circular base can also be used for some applications. Some new world barens are similar in shape to the traditional one with small metal ball bearings embedded in the bottom surface that generate the high point contact pressures (supplied by the braided cord) and have the low friction (offered by the bamboo leaf covering) of a traditional brayer.  Another interesting baren is one developed by Professor Seishi Ozakus and made from a bundle of bamboo toothpicks.<sup id=\"cite_ref-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>Nik Semenoff has developed a palm press that serves as a baren replacement, made with a number of roller bearings alternating on two close spaced shafts in a small hand held mounting.  The bearings have negligible friction and the pressures achievable are suitable for some <a href=\"/wiki/Offset_printing\" title=\"Offset printing\">offset</a> <a href=\"/wiki/Lithography\" title=\"Lithography\">lithography</a> printing, though wider spacing of fewer contact points may make it less suited for traditional wood cut printing.\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Baren_(printing_tool)&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-McGregorIshida2016-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-McGregorIshida2016_1-0\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation book\">Dr. Mark McGregor; Mariko Ishida (23 April 2016). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://books.google.com/books?id=aPbIDQAAQBAJ&amp;pg=PT50\"><i>Ukiyo-e: Secrets of the floating world</i></a>. Vyiha Publishing. pp.&#160;50\u2013. <a href=\"/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number\" title=\"International Standard Book Number\">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href=\"/wiki/Special:BookSources/978-988-13004-3-0\" title=\"Special:BookSources/978-988-13004-3-0\">978-988-13004-3-0</a>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Ukiyo-e%3A+Secrets+of+the+floating+world&amp;rft.pages=50-&amp;rft.pub=Vyiha+Publishing&amp;rft.date=2016-04-23&amp;rft.isbn=978-988-13004-3-0&amp;rft.au=Dr.+Mark+McGregor&amp;rft.au=Mariko+Ishida&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fbooks.google.com%2Fbooks%3Fid%3DaPbIDQAAQBAJ%26pg%3DPT50&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ABaren+%28printing+tool%29\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-hiroshi-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\">^ <a href=\"#cite_ref-hiroshi_2-0\"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-hiroshi_2-1\"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation book\"><a href=\"/wiki/Hiroshi_Yoshida\" title=\"Hiroshi Yoshida\">Hiroshi Yoshida</a> (1939). <i>Japanese Wood-block Printing</i>. Sanseido Company, Tokyo and Osaka.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Japanese+Wood-block+Printing&amp;rft.pub=Sanseido+Company%2C+Tokyo+and+Osaka&amp;rft.date=1939&amp;rft.au=Hiroshi+Yoshida&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ABaren+%28printing+tool%29\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-3\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-3\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://homepage.usask.ca/~nis715/S%20Ozakus.htm\">Professor Seishi Ozakus' Toothpick Baren</a></span>\n</li>\n</ol></div></div>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"External_links\">External links</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Baren_(printing_tool)&amp;action=edit&amp;section=4\" title=\"Edit section: External links\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul><li><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.scn-net.ne.jp/~kikuhide/hon-baren.html\">Hidehiko Goto's website</a> (in Japanese)</li>\n<li><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://imcclains.com/catalog/baren/index.html\">Barens at McCain's printing supplies</a></li>\n<li><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.barenforum.org/\">The Baren Forum for Woodblock Printmaking</a></li>\n<li><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.mossworks.com/docs/PrintEtchingsWithAPalmPress.pdf\">Printing Etchings with a Palm Press</a> - instructions for using Palm Press made from furniture casters</li></ul>\n<table class=\"metadata plainlinks stub\" role=\"presentation\" style=\"background:transparent\"><tbody><tr><td><a href=\"/wiki/File:Tools.svg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"Stub icon\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/w